**Version Used**: 16.4.2

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```cs
interface I<T>
{
    T M<TArg>(TArg arg) where TArg : T;
}

class C : I<int>
{
    int I<int>.M<TArg>(TArg arg)
    {
        return arg;
        return (int)arg;
    }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:
The code should compile without errors. `I<int>.M<TArg>` can only be instantiated with `int` and so both conversions must always succeed (they should be no-op). This code works when `string` is used instead of `int`.

**Actual Behavior**:
First `return`: CS0029	Cannot implicitly convert type 'TArg' to 'int'
Second `return`: CS0030	Cannot convert type 'TArg' to 'int'

